<subSubSection pageId="68" pageNumber="69" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="68.[151,1436,506,732]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,626,652]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Similar to several uniformly brown species, from which it can be distinguished by the presence of a long, hooked, dorsal metatibial spur (
<figureCitation box="[705,795,666,692]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,255,1079,1103]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,194,1055]" captionTargetId="figure-129@8.[153,1433,194,1055]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Metatibial spurs in Exochomoscirtes. A) E. dilaticornis sp. nov.; B) E. discoidalis (Pic); C) E. longispinus sp. nov.; D) E. nigromarginatus sp. nov.; E) E. picturatus sp. nov.; F) E. takizawai sp. nov." pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
) in the males. Another distinctive feature is extraordinarily elongated penis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
